well, you'll probably know where the Netherlands is. If not, I refer you to Google Earth. So let's

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:05.119
start off with the approach now, which is, I guess, the most important part of this

00:09:05.119 --> 00:09:09.760
presentation. But a little disclaimer to begin with. You have this saying, under pressure,

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:13.200
everything becomes fluid. We use it a lot in Dutch as well.

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:20.760
Onder druk wordt alles vloeibaar, we say. And I put this at the start of the main part of this

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:29.640
presentation, because this is not a normal organization in COVID-19 times. And this is also,

00:09:29.799 --> 00:09:37.280
it's not a normal era, so to speak. So I was thinking, what is it that I want to share in my

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:41.559
presentation? I want to share something that you can actually take with you to your organization

00:09:41.559 --> 00:09:47.599
also in normal times, because a lot of things were different now. There was more money to get things

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:55.719
done, there was less bureaucracy, etc. But keep this in mind as I continue my talk. And I tried to

00:09:55.719 --> 00:10:00.599
really focus in on the things that you could take with you to your organization during normal times,

00:10:00.599 --> 00:10:07.400
hopefully very soon. So as I said before, I was faced with a problem. And I really wanted to

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:13.479
understand this problem properly before continuing. So I wanted to have a clear view of who our

00:10:13.479 --> 00:10:20.039
customers were, which is not a term you hear often in the public domain organization, but it's really

00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:26.440
relevant. Who are we working for exactly? Is it the decision makers? Is it the researchers? We decided

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:33.200
that it is actually the doctors and epidemiologists that work at these MHSs that we want to inform. So

00:10:33.200 --> 00:10:39.679
we had a clear definition of our customer. What kind of data do we have? Well, we have the source

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:44.960
investigation and contact tracing data. So anytime you test positive for COVID, you will be called by

00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:50.280
one of the employees of the MHS when you live in the Netherlands. And they will ask you where have you

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:55.880
been? Who have you been in contact with? Where do you think that you may have contracted the virus in

00:10:55.880 --> 00:11:02.280
all likelihood? And this data is being sent to the RIVM. And we use this to create, well, let's say

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:07.400
actionable insights. This was at least our wish from the very beginning. We want to not just create

00:11:07.400 --> 00:11:13.880
insights on things that people want to know, but there needs to be some action tied to the insight.

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:21.520
The doctors and epidemiologists in the MHSs, they advise the executive branch. So we wanted to give

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:27.719
them the insights to have as good as an advice as possible to eventually, this was one of the goals,

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:35.400
bust clusters. This is what the woman that hired me actually told me that they wanted to go busting

00:11:35.400 --> 00:11:41.039
clusters. So I was like, what does that mean? This is actually an epidemiological term. And I thought

00:11:41.039 --> 00:11:47.679
to myself, that is a great name for an R-Shiny application. So I kept using that. And eventually,

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:54.000
when we went to production and started opening our application to doctors and epidemiologists, I was

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:00.799
like, maybe we should find a more formal name for this application. But this doctor I spoke to said,

00:12:00.799 --> 00:12:06.119
no, no, no, you definitely need to keep it called the cluster buster, because that is a great name.

00:12:06.119 --> 00:12:13.320
So it's been called the cluster buster ever since. And I'm very happy that we stuck with it. So this is an

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:18.320
example of what happened in the Netherlands. I believe this happened in the US as well. This is a meat

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:26.599
processing plant that was shut down because there were too many positive COVID tests reported back to

00:12:26.599 --> 00:12:32.679
this facility. They were not adhering to the guidelines. So this one got closed. This happened over 200

00:12:32.679 --> 00:12:40.000
times, I believe, in the Netherlands in 2020. So yeah, giving advice on where COVID clusters is

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:48.320
actually a really relevant thing to do. Another part of the problem is not all 25 regions had proper access

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:52.880
to actionable insights. This was obviously a main part of the problem. They did not have the insights.

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:57.640
They did have the data because they collected, but they did not have sometimes the analytical talent or

00:12:57.640 --> 00:13:08.520
the tools to come up with insights that were valuable. So some did, some had great tools, they had great

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:14.719
dashboards, there was already an R Shiny dashboard produced in one of these MHSs. Some had great reports.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:22.320
So one of the main questions that we asked ourselves is, what are the best practices that we see in these

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:30.119
MHSs? And can we replicate them? And can we redistribute them to all 25? So that was one of the main goals we had in

00:13:30.119 --> 00:13:40.039
mind. To do this, I first had to have a clear understanding of whether or not it was possible to share insights.

00:13:40.039 --> 00:13:44.919
And obviously, you have some prerequisites when you want to do this, you have some legal boundaries, we cannot

00:13:44.919 --> 00:13:53.000
share all the data, you have GDPR, privacy regulations in every country, I believe everyone in this meeting has their own

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:58.760
version of GDPR, we had as well. So there were some boundaries and limitations to what we were allowed to share.

00:13:58.799 --> 00:14:04.760
Obviously, the data had some limitations. And the technology has some limitations. So I needed to have a clear

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:13.400
understanding of what our limitations and possibilities were. But once I had this understanding, my advice was actually to

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:22.400
move forward with with R Shiny. So I use this metaphor a lot, but it was a little bit of a 100 meter hurdle run, like what are the

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:29.799
hurdles that we need to pass one by one in order to get to our final goal? So do we have legal hurdles? Do we have technological

00:14:29.799 --> 00:14:36.159
hurdles? Do we lack some data? But can we get it? These are the kinds of questions that we asked ourselves in the very early

00:14:36.159 --> 00:14:47.559
beginning. So finally, I said, Yeah, well, I think R Shiny is actually the right tool for the job. And it was actually a logical choice in my

00:14:47.559 --> 00:14:55.599
view. Why? Because a lot of the data preparation, COVID-19 data in the Netherlands was already done in R. A lot of people working at the

00:14:55.599 --> 00:15:06.039
RIVM are familiar with R. And there was already some experience with R Shiny applications. So based on my prior experience, and my

00:15:06.039 --> 00:15:14.760
first weeks of investigation at the RIVM, I knew for a fact that we could produce value with R Shiny. But this was just me. R Shiny is

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:23.760
still quite a new tool, although some of you might disagree. But for organizations, it's still at some point quite new. So I had to do some

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:34.919
convincing. So what I did was I created a prototype of which you see a screenshot here. And I use this to show that R Shiny can actually

00:15:34.919 --> 00:15:47.359
produce great looking and valuable dashboards, valuable insights. This one is still online. And I guess I can probably share a link to

00:15:47.359 --> 00:15:50.760
this at some point, maybe later on, Rachel.

00:15:53.599 --> 00:16:02.799
People can look at it themselves. Yeah. So yeah, it's probably most fun if you can just click through it yourselves. But I created this

00:16:02.799 --> 00:16:09.559
prototype, because I still needed to convince some people that R Shiny was actually the right tool for the job. And this is highly

00:16:09.559 --> 00:16:22.359
recommended. Yeah, they got really enthusiastic. So eventually, I got the green light. And they said, Well, shoot, we trust you. Yeah, let's go

00:16:22.359 --> 00:16:32.320
for it and create a team to do whatever you think is necessary to create this application and share insights with these MHSs. So I got the

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:42.400
green light to build my own team. I wanted it to be as vertically integrated as possible. I wanted a team to be able to produce 80 to 90% of the

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:52.000
application all by itself. Obviously, some of the work is too specialized to do within your team. So we had to rely on the IT department a bit as

00:16:52.000 --> 00:17:01.159
well. Joep will talk a little bit more about that later on. We were meeting very often. Well, let's say three times a week, we had a daily stand up

00:17:01.159 --> 00:17:11.479
meeting. And we would be meeting in between those obviously, pretty often. So we had a sort of an agile working style. Let's say it was rapid

00:17:11.479 --> 00:17:20.439
iteration, it was not agile to the to the T, but it was agile in spirit. And there was a lot of enthusiasm. I think this is really a result of

00:17:20.439 --> 00:17:30.560
vertical integration and working in an agile way. Because we were capable of doing so much ourselves. At some times we we got a request for an

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:40.959
insight, and we could deliver the same day. And that is a great way of working. This is also thanks to to our shiny impart and to the special skills

00:17:40.959 --> 00:17:50.119
that we had in our team. So this vertically integrated way of working really got really helped us and made us very enthusiastic in the process.

00:17:51.119 --> 00:18:03.119
So this is our team. I stole this picture from from Joep. I believe he drew it himself, which is amazing. I didn't know that he had that talent as well. But this is our team.

00:18:03.119 --> 00:18:17.119
We're seven of us right now. But we started off with a very small team with myself and Yossi. She is my colleague that is responsible for the coordination of doctors and epidemiologists that work at the

00:18:17.119 --> 00:18:37.119
RIVM. So we started off with Yossi, with Joep and with myself, but we gradually built towards a larger team. And each and every one of them had their own part to play. So this is the team, seven people, but I think all in all, it's probably two full time employees. It

00:18:37.119 --> 00:18:51.119
counts up to two FTE that we used to create this product, which, in my view, is still really quite amazing that we were able to do so much with with so little. This is probably quite a convincing argument for decision makers in your organization as well.

00:18:52.119 --> 00:19:20.119
So January 2021, there was some understanding of the problem. The prerequisites were met, we had our weapon of choice, which was our Shiny, and there was a team. So now what? We were all ready to go. But yeah, what was the approach? And I think that this is the single most important question in this entire process is how do you allocate as much of your energy as possible towards creating value?

00:19:20.119 --> 00:19:42.119
And obviously, to be able to do this, you need to have a clear definition of value. And as I said before, I'm not a doctor, nor am I an epidemiologist. So nor am I an end user of the application. So we said to ourselves, we need some sort of a feedback loop from the users themselves, from the experts themselves.

00:19:42.119 --> 00:20:10.119
So we put together an advisory board, Yossi and me, containing of doctors and epidemiologists that work at the MHS. So they were the representatives, so to speak, of our user group. Together with them, we had a strong focus on actionable insights as much as possible. Obviously, sometimes you create an insight just because it provides some background information that's useful in getting a situational awareness.

00:20:10.119 --> 00:20:25.119
But we were definitely focused towards creating insights that could lead to some action in practice, not just a nice to know thing.

00:20:25.119 --> 00:20:45.119
For me personally, my most important role in this advisory board was balancing between requests and possibilities. So oftentimes, the advisory board would put down a request, shoot, is this something that you can make? And I would balance this out with legal possibilities as well as technological possibilities.

00:20:45.119 --> 00:21:04.119
And we would have weekly meetings with this advisory board. So here you can see this rapid iteration, weekly meetings. We would provide feedback on Fridays on what we did, and we would continue to look forward at trying to find new insights that we could produce that would help out even more.

00:21:04.119 --> 00:21:30.119
So this is one of the sentences that I show through this advisory board every week. This is the task of the advisory board. It isn't Dutch, but it doesn't really matter for now. What it was, it was a constant reminder that we had to work towards creating valuable insights. So very strong focus on that. Let's not waste energy doing things for fun. Let's work towards insights that actually add some value.

00:21:31.119 --> 00:21:50.119
So this is the structure that we end up with. All the way at the top, you see our user group. They are represented by the advisory board. And through the advisory board, we collect requests, the development team collect requests, and they start working on realizing those.

00:21:50.119 --> 00:22:08.119
And obviously, in the background, there's a lot of specialists that helped us out with, for example, legal questions or IT-related questions. So yeah, I think all in all, just around 30 people maybe helped us out with what I said, legal and IT matters.

00:22:08.119 --> 00:22:34.119
So what did we end up with? We ended up with an application, an R-Shiny application that provided insights into vaccination. So what you see here is a map with the vaccination rate, I believe it's called, for every neighborhood and every age group. And we also combined this with the amount of positive reports. So this is a bivariate choroplethic map.

00:22:35.119 --> 00:22:49.119
So you have the bivariate part is the vaccination rate versus the amount of infections in the last week. Everything you see here, obviously, is fake data. We have some tables. I'm not going into depth into all of those.

00:22:49.119 --> 00:23:07.119
This is a visualization of clusters. So on the left here, you see some of these clusters. This could be a workplace, maybe, or a school or a nursing home. And if you clicked on one of those, on the right, you would see where the linked clusters were situated.

00:23:07.119 --> 00:23:27.119
So this is one of the requests that was put forward by the advisory board. And thanks to R-Shiny, actually, we could realize this. I'm not sure if we could have done this in any other tool. For us, it was really relatively easy to create these kinds of insights with R-Shiny.

00:23:27.119 --> 00:23:43.119
So I seldom had to sell a no to a request from the advisory board, which was a nice way of working. Yeah, we used Sparklines. Joep will talk a little bit more about the packages we used to create all these insights.

00:23:44.119 --> 00:23:58.119
So finally, we had a pretty cool application. We thought it was very valuable, but obviously, this didn't sell itself. So I had to give a lot of presentations. I think I spoke to almost every region in the Netherlands.

00:23:58.119 --> 00:24:15.119
We have had some newsletters with regular updates. And obviously, we are doing a little bit of work on outreach, because we don't think that the product sells itself, so to speak. So there was a little bit of technology push, if you can call it that.

00:24:15.119 --> 00:24:38.119
But eventually, we started noticing that a lot of people started asking for authorization. So all in all, now we have almost 400 doctors and epidemiologists that use our tool. So that's what we did in the meantime. For the last couple of months, let's say the last 10 months already, we have been producing insights.

00:24:39.119 --> 00:25:06.119
We are approaching 400 users, and they are from all 25 MHS regions. So this is something that we're actually pretty proud of. We know that the application is being used. We know this because we track it quantitatively. Obviously, also, we ask it to the MHSes, how do you use it? Why do you use it? And what can we improve? I literally call them or send them an email to get some qualitative feedback as well.

00:25:07.119 --> 00:25:32.119
They use these insights to stay up to date on COVID-19 clusters. And they have also used our application for the allocation of mobile vaccination units. So they have a limited number of mobile vaccination units. And one of the questions they ask themselves, obviously, is what is the best place to locate this mobile vaccination unit, which could be a bus or something like that. And they use the Cluster Buster to find the optimal spot for that.

00:25:32.119 --> 00:26:00.119
And one of the nice, how you say this, side effects was that the data quality actually improved because the MHSes started using the Cluster Buster. So they finally saw the reason for keeping track of all different types of data. We gave them back insights, and this motivated them to really pay attention to the quality of their data.

00:26:02.119 --> 00:26:27.119
Yeah, well, I put this in. This is just to say that we are already working on our next application. This is one that I hope that we will release, let's say, in the next month or so. And this is, we will take everything we learned from the Cluster Buster and put it in our next application. This, I hope, and we are working towards this, is going to be open source.

00:26:27.119 --> 00:26:40.119
So I'm hoping to share this, share the code behind this application so all of you can see how we did this exactly and can create your own tiny new Cluster Busters for whatever use you prefer.

00:26:41.119 --> 00:27:04.119
So main takeaways for me, I guess the most important ones are have a very clear understanding of the problem, which I talked about a lot before. Create a convincing prototype. If your organization is not already used to using R-Shiny, especially for a public use, create a convincing prototype or just show what we have made. It's ready for your use, I guess.

00:27:05.119 --> 00:27:13.119
Vertical integration helped us out a lot because we could create insights very quickly, so rapid iteration was possible.

00:27:14.119 --> 00:27:26.119
Very important to have a clear definition of value. So for us, we had our advisory board. I say here clear-ish definition of value because what is valuable may change over time.

00:27:27.119 --> 00:27:39.119
So at first, we said that it would be very valuable to have insight into clusters of COVID-19. This is still valuable information, but at some point, we started focusing a little bit more on insights into vaccination data.

00:27:40.119 --> 00:27:49.119
So the definition of value may change, obviously, over time. Incorporate your user feedback. Keep a strong focus on what your definition of value is.

00:27:50.119 --> 00:27:59.119
I noticed that it's important to promote your products. Don't think that it will sell itself. Well, it might eventually, but really do some promoting and ask why a lot.

00:28:00.119 --> 00:28:10.119
This may be particularly necessary if you work in the public domain where it's not always just about efficiency. So you need to ask why a lot. Why do we do this?

00:28:11.119 --> 00:28:27.119
And finally, for us at least, I think that R-Shiny was an excellent choice, especially because we got to develop our insights as close as possible to the wish of our end user, and I think that is very valuable.

00:28:28.119 --> 00:28:36.119
And this is what got us so enthusiastic in using R-Shiny. So I guess that's it. Yeah, that was my last slide already.

