00:32:51.119 --> 00:32:57.119
To give a short introduction, I'm Jorg Spijker. I'm a geochemist at the National Institute for Public Health and Environment.

00:32:58.119 --> 00:33:05.119
I work at the environmental department and I already work with R for, I think, at least 20 years or something.

00:33:06.119 --> 00:33:08.119
I do a lot of data analysis with R.

00:33:09.119 --> 00:33:15.119
And the last years in our division, we already had to put out some shiny applications on the internet.

00:33:16.119 --> 00:33:17.119
We used Docker technology for that.

00:33:18.119 --> 00:33:23.119
That was the reason that Jorg asked me for this project because he needed some back-end engineer to do this work.

00:33:24.119 --> 00:33:32.119
So although I'm a data scientist, I wasn't called for my geochemical knowledge because that wasn't needed, but mostly for my engineering skills.

00:33:33.119 --> 00:33:37.119
So that was my role in this team.

00:33:40.119 --> 00:33:43.119
Well, Jorg already told something about the municipal health services.

00:33:44.119 --> 00:33:45.119
They collect a lot of data from you.

00:33:46.119 --> 00:33:49.119
Let's consider that that's you somewhere out there having a COVID test.

00:33:50.119 --> 00:33:56.119
And they collect your name, your address, your phone number, your social security number, if you are affected or not.

00:33:57.119 --> 00:34:00.119
And if you are affected, they do a source investigation, a contact tracing.

00:34:01.119 --> 00:34:05.119
They ask about your whereabouts, the people you're in contact with, et cetera.

00:34:06.119 --> 00:34:08.120
And they also collect data about your vaccination.

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:12.120
So that's quite a lot of sensitive data about you.

00:34:13.120 --> 00:34:16.120
Now, this is us.

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:18.120
We are a data science team.

00:34:19.120 --> 00:34:22.120
And our assignment was a little bit rephrased than what Jorg told us.

00:34:23.120 --> 00:34:33.120
But they asked us to just fiddle with that very private data, create some information out of it, put it on the internet, and make sure only people who are allowed to see it can actually see it.

00:34:34.120 --> 00:34:39.120
And this is actually the moment you have to get out of your chair because you start yelling at us.

00:34:40.120 --> 00:34:52.120
Because as data scientists, how can you be sure that that very sensitive data is in our good hands and that we have enough knowledge about security to make this application actually secure?

00:34:53.120 --> 00:34:58.120
So actually, from an engineering point of view, we have three challenges.

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:00.120
First, you have to create this information.

00:35:00.120 --> 00:35:03.120
You have to create the dashboard, which was the least of our concerns.

00:35:04.120 --> 00:35:07.120
You have to work with all the privacy issues.

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:14.120
In Europe, you have the GDPR, the General Data Protection Regulations, which is very strict about privacy.

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:22.120
And we're talking about personal medical data, which is the most sensitive data that we have.

00:35:23.120 --> 00:35:27.120
And we have to do a privacy impact assessment.

00:35:27.120 --> 00:35:30.120
We have to talk to our privacy officers.

00:35:31.120 --> 00:35:32.120
And that's a lot of paperwork.

00:35:33.120 --> 00:35:41.120
And part of the paperwork is to describe how we physically, in IT terminology, secure our data.

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:43.120
And we are data scientists.

00:35:44.120 --> 00:35:45.120
We're not security experts.

00:35:46.120 --> 00:35:48.120
So this was the biggest challenge.

00:35:49.120 --> 00:35:56.120
Before I go into how we solved it, I'll show you a little bit about the data flow that we have.

00:35:57.120 --> 00:36:00.120
Here we have the landscape with all these municipal health services.

00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:07.120
They collect all the data and part of the data they send to the RFPM using a myriad of systems.

00:36:08.120 --> 00:36:11.120
There are about eight different systems within these NHSs.

00:36:12.120 --> 00:36:15.120
This data is collected in a database or two.

00:36:16.120 --> 00:36:22.120
And then we have our own data science team, the insurance department, which actually extracts data from these databases

00:36:23.120 --> 00:36:31.120
and creates all kinds of data products, reports, graphs, visualizations, whatsoever, which are used for combating this COVID crisis.

00:36:32.120 --> 00:36:36.120
And all these data products are stored on a network file storage.

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:39.120
And we take it from there.

00:36:40.120 --> 00:36:44.120
So this is from the backend side.

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:53.120
Now, if you're going to look to the other side, this is how you want to make this data available again to the NHS.

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:59.120
We decided to create this application using a Docker environment.

00:37:00.120 --> 00:37:02.120
We use an OpenShift Kubernetes environment for that.

00:37:03.120 --> 00:37:18.120
And what we did is that we said, all right, we put this web application in a DMZ, which is an open piece of a network, which is open to the world.

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:24.120
And we use our F5 proxy server for the authorization.

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:34.120
The biggest advancement is that this proxy server was a building block, a service, which was provided by our IT department.

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:37.120
So they were taking care of the authorization.

00:37:38.120 --> 00:37:42.120
And it means that the people at the NHS can log in using their own credentials.

00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:46.120
It's like logging in using a Google account to some other website.

00:37:46.120 --> 00:37:57.120
So logging in with their own credentials, passing through the proxy, and then having access to the application.

00:37:58.120 --> 00:38:04.120
And also, the thing that we did was that if somebody logs in, then we know which user it is.

00:38:05.120 --> 00:38:14.120
So then, based on the username, we provide the user with only the data that he or she is allowed to see.

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:31.120
It means that if somebody makes an error here at the NHS and authorize somebody who is allowed to log in, but we haven't received any message or we don't know him, then the person will get access to the application, but don't have access to the data.

00:38:32.120 --> 00:38:43.120
So in case of a data breach, it means that this application isn't accessible if you don't have an authorization.

00:38:44.120 --> 00:38:53.120
So if you are some bad guy, somebody who wants to do something with that application, it means that you don't even come near it.

00:38:54.120 --> 00:39:06.120
However, if you can get near the application and start hanging around, it means that you only can have access to the container environment and to the data contained in that container environment.

00:39:07.120 --> 00:39:15.120
The internal data, the file storage, it was completely blocked off because there was a one-way firewall between it.

00:39:16.120 --> 00:39:20.120
So the only thing we could do is push our data through the container and it's not the other way around.

00:39:20.120 --> 00:39:23.120
But this was one way to also secure the data.

00:39:24.120 --> 00:39:32.120
And these were all services or building blocks or tools provided by the IT department and also stuff which the IT department could maintain.

00:39:33.120 --> 00:39:40.120
So we can deliver an application and we still can trust on the experts of the IT department securing everything.

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:47.120
If you look at the total, let's first have a look at our own process.

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:55.120
What we did is that we had this information created by the data scientist team on this network.

00:39:56.120 --> 00:40:01.120
And we had a small Linux virtual machine running all kinds of cron jobs and doing the data preparation.

00:40:02.120 --> 00:40:05.120
In the beginning, the machine was doing quite a lot of heavy lifting on the data.

00:40:05.120 --> 00:40:09.120
Nowadays, a lot of this heavy lifting is done by the data science team.

00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:13.120
And we only have to do some small adjustments to the data.

00:40:14.120 --> 00:40:25.120
But on this machine, a SQLite database is created and this database is pushed through this one-way only firewall onto the container platform which is running Docker containers.

00:40:26.120 --> 00:40:29.120
And these Docker containers contain the application.

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:34.120
And of course we use a Git repository with the code.

00:40:35.120 --> 00:40:38.120
And this combined completes the application.

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:49.120
So this total picture of how we created this architecture is that we have our data science teams who are doing the first step of the data preparation.

00:40:50.120 --> 00:40:54.120
Then it's our team who is actually creating the database and the application.

00:40:54.120 --> 00:41:04.120
But by launching the application and making the application available to the outer world, that's done on this container platform which was managed by the IT department.

00:41:05.120 --> 00:41:12.120
That means that we can focus on creating an application while all the security issues are the responsibility of the IT department.

00:41:13.120 --> 00:41:20.120
And these guys, they have the right experts to make sure that only the right people can access this application.

00:41:20.120 --> 00:41:24.120
So this is how we solve our biggest issue around security.

00:41:25.120 --> 00:41:29.120
And these are all kind of building blocks which were available within our institute.

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:32.120
It took a while to stick everything together.

00:41:33.120 --> 00:41:37.120
But now we have an environment which we think is pretty secure.

00:41:38.120 --> 00:41:40.120
At least secure enough for this kind of sensitive data.

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:44.120
So this is a bit about the architecture.

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:47.120
Now let's focus a little bit more on the application.

00:41:47.120 --> 00:41:49.120
Now let's focus a little bit more on the application.

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:53.120
But before that I want to talk about our team.

00:41:54.120 --> 00:41:56.120
Stuart already introduced us.

00:41:57.120 --> 00:42:01.120
In the beginning we were just a bunch of data scientists.

00:42:02.120 --> 00:42:04.120
But an application like this requires teamwork.

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:09.120
So we decided pretty early already on certain team roles.

00:42:10.120 --> 00:42:12.120
Who is going to do what.

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:15.120
In my case I do the backend engineering.

00:42:15.120 --> 00:42:17.120
Jolien did the visualization.

00:42:18.120 --> 00:42:20.120
Stuart did a lot of talking, etc.

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:25.120
And we also had these regular standard meetings.

00:42:26.120 --> 00:42:29.120
So we had very short communications with each other.

00:42:30.120 --> 00:42:35.120
And we also decided very quickly to put everything on GitHub in a private repository.

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:38.120
That means the code, not the data of course.

00:42:39.120 --> 00:42:42.120
And we decided to work with branches and with issue branches, etc.

00:42:42.120 --> 00:42:43.120
And we decided to work with branches and with issue branches, etc.

00:42:44.120 --> 00:42:49.120
Just like my classic teams are used to do.

00:42:50.120 --> 00:42:55.120
And we created several containers for several stages of our application.

00:42:56.120 --> 00:42:58.120
So we have a development version.

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:00.120
This is just for us developers.

00:43:01.120 --> 00:43:03.120
We have a testing version just to make sure everything works.

00:43:04.120 --> 00:43:05.120
We have an acceptance version.

00:43:06.120 --> 00:43:07.120
This is a version which is also accessible from the outside.

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:10.120
It can only be accessed from the inside.

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:12.120
So we can show some new things.

00:43:13.120 --> 00:43:14.120
And we have a production version.

00:43:15.120 --> 00:43:22.120
And using this kind of tiered versions,

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:26.120
it means that when we are at the moment that we want to put something in production,

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:34.120
we are pretty sure it's solid, it works, and users want to work with it.

00:43:35.120 --> 00:43:37.120
Well, we chose Vashani, obviously.

00:43:37.120 --> 00:43:45.120
But one of the things we also decided is that we are going to split up this whole Shiny application in Shiny modules.

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:50.120
If you create any serious Shiny applications, I think you should use Shiny modules.

00:43:51.120 --> 00:43:57.120
With modules, you make it much more easier to maintain and to reuse your code.

00:43:58.120 --> 00:43:59.120
I'll come to that later.

00:44:00.120 --> 00:44:02.120
As I said, we use SQLite as a database.

00:44:03.120 --> 00:44:04.120
Powering the app.

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:06.120
SQLite is very portable.

00:44:07.120 --> 00:44:09.120
It's just one single file, which is very easy to move around.

00:44:10.120 --> 00:44:14.120
And we use the pool package to access the SQLite.

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:18.120
For the visualizations, we use HighCharge.

00:44:19.120 --> 00:44:25.120
And HighCharge is a visualization library, which is almost the default for the Dutch government.

00:44:26.120 --> 00:44:30.120
You need a paid license for it, so it's not free.

00:44:31.120 --> 00:44:36.120
But we have the license and the visualizations just look cool.

00:44:37.120 --> 00:44:40.120
We use Xamalux to track usage.

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:46.120
And for the visualizations of the maps, we use Leaflet and Simple Features.

00:44:47.120 --> 00:44:50.120
And we also use Sparklines, so our tables look pretty cool.

00:44:51.120 --> 00:44:52.120
These are the main packages.

00:44:52.120 --> 00:44:54.120
I will go into some details.

00:44:55.120 --> 00:44:56.120
First, these modules.

00:44:57.120 --> 00:45:03.120
If you look at the application that we created, the total application contains about 75 different visualizations.

00:45:04.120 --> 00:45:05.120
However, there's a lot of reuse.

00:45:06.120 --> 00:45:10.120
It means that we can create 75 visualizations with about 25 modules.

00:45:11.120 --> 00:45:14.120
This also includes modules for titles and stuff like that.

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:19.120
And reuse makes it very easy to use.

00:45:19.120 --> 00:45:25.120
And reuse makes it very easy that you can reuse all your code.

00:45:26.120 --> 00:45:33.120
For example, there's a setting page in this application where you can see what the affections are,

00:45:34.120 --> 00:45:37.120
depending on different settings, like nursery, homes, or schools.

00:45:38.120 --> 00:45:44.120
And these pages, they contain all the same visuals.

00:45:44.120 --> 00:45:47.120
But if you use modules, you just create one module.

00:45:48.120 --> 00:45:50.120
And a module is one single visual.

00:45:51.120 --> 00:45:57.120
And you can use that visual on different pages and on different locations inside your applications.

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:01.120
And also for maintaining your code, it's also very easy.

00:46:02.120 --> 00:46:06.120
Because if there's something wrong with the visualization, you immediately know where to look at,

00:46:07.120 --> 00:46:10.120
at which part of the code is causing the troubles.

00:46:11.120 --> 00:46:18.120
What we also did is that we organized our code and what we use, what we call subscripts.

00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:24.120
If you look at the server.r file, for such a huge application, it's about hundreds, maybe thousands of lines.

00:46:25.120 --> 00:46:32.120
And we just chopped it up in different sections and sourced it using a source local command.

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:35.120
And this makes also the code more maintainable.

00:46:36.120 --> 00:46:41.120
It also means that if you work as a team, it's much easier to work with one person on a single file.

00:46:42.120 --> 00:46:48.120
Because if you work with multiple persons on the same file, you have the risk of conflict.

00:46:49.120 --> 00:46:52.120
So it makes things a little bit more difficult.

00:46:53.120 --> 00:46:59.120
So that was one of the things that we also did, to split up the code.

00:47:00.120 --> 00:47:04.120
And make it easier to maintain the application or to add new features.

00:47:05.120 --> 00:47:12.120
One of the things that was very important for us is the tracking of the usage of the applications.

00:47:13.120 --> 00:47:16.120
We really wanted to know how are users interacting with our applications.

00:47:17.120 --> 00:47:19.120
Of course, you can ask what they're doing.

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:24.120
But it's also nice to have some quantitative data about it.

00:47:25.120 --> 00:47:27.120
So we use ShinyLogs as a package.

00:47:28.120 --> 00:47:34.120
And I think ShinyLogs is a great package for that.

00:47:35.120 --> 00:47:37.120
However, there were some privacy issues with ShinyLogs.

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:42.120
One of the things with ShinyLogs was it was recording the IP number.

00:47:43.120 --> 00:47:49.120
And the IP number is an identifiable number which can identify a person.

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:52.120
And according to our privacy statement, we cannot record it.

00:47:53.120 --> 00:47:55.120
So what we did is that we wrote some functions.

00:47:55.120 --> 00:48:01.120
So now we rewrote some functions of ShinyLogs and then overloaded them in the library.

00:48:02.120 --> 00:48:03.120
It was in the assigned namespace.

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:09.120
So we made some little adjustments to this package without actually altering the package.

00:48:10.120 --> 00:48:19.120
And what ShinyLogs does is store all the data that has also an SQLite database.

00:48:20.120 --> 00:48:23.120
We created even a separate dashboard out of it.

00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:26.120
So we could just follow the user interaction.

00:48:28.120 --> 00:48:29.120
All right.

00:48:30.120 --> 00:48:31.120
These were just some details.

00:48:32.120 --> 00:48:35.120
Of course, when you're working with an application, you're always thinking,

00:48:36.120 --> 00:48:38.120
what are the next steps that we're going to do?

00:48:39.120 --> 00:48:42.120
One of the things I really like to look into is using regression tests.

00:48:43.120 --> 00:48:47.120
We are creating a Shiny application.

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:50.120
But testing takes quite a lot of time.

00:48:50.120 --> 00:48:53.120
If you can automate this somehow,

00:48:54.120 --> 00:48:59.120
it will really contribute to your speed of coding and speed of adding new features.

00:49:00.120 --> 00:49:02.120
It's not implemented right now in Cluster Buster,

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:06.120
but we're thinking of it to do it for the next version.

00:49:07.120 --> 00:49:13.120
Also, one of the things that we want to look into is the communication

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:16.120
between all these reactive elements in such an application.

00:49:17.120 --> 00:49:20.120
We think it can be more efficient, but it's also,

00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:24.120
if you're working with it, it always gives me headaches.

00:49:25.120 --> 00:49:29.120
So we really have to think about it once.

00:49:30.120 --> 00:49:31.120
And also for other applications,

00:49:32.120 --> 00:49:35.120
I'm not sure if we're going to apply it to the next version of Cluster Buster,

00:49:36.120 --> 00:49:37.120
but at least for other applications we're working with,

00:49:38.120 --> 00:49:41.120
we're thinking about using frameworks like Golem or something else

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:47.120
just to make the development cycle a little bit faster.

00:49:48.120 --> 00:49:50.120
And we really like to make this open source.

00:49:51.120 --> 00:49:53.120
However, it's not on top of our list.

00:49:54.120 --> 00:49:55.120
We're very busy.

00:49:56.120 --> 00:49:58.120
The COVID numbers are soaring high here.

00:49:59.120 --> 00:50:02.120
But we really like to make it open source.

00:50:03.120 --> 00:50:07.120
So maybe in the future we put it somewhere so you can have a look at it.

00:50:08.120 --> 00:50:10.120
And of course, we're also thinking about Cluster Buster 2.0,

00:50:11.120 --> 00:50:13.120
the next version of this application.

00:50:16.120 --> 00:50:19.120
So in summary, as a data scientist,

00:50:20.120 --> 00:50:22.120
you like to make shiny applications where you have to be aware

00:50:23.120 --> 00:50:24.120
that you're not a security oriented programmer.

00:50:25.120 --> 00:50:26.120
So make sure that somebody else, in our case,

00:50:27.120 --> 00:50:29.120
the IT department is taking care of the security

00:50:30.120 --> 00:50:34.120
and that they provide a safe environment,

00:50:34.120 --> 00:50:35.120
in this case, a Docker environment,

00:50:36.120 --> 00:50:38.120
where you just can put in your application.

00:50:39.120 --> 00:50:41.120
So you have to really think about your infrastructure.

00:50:42.120 --> 00:50:43.120
And that means go talk to these IT people.

00:50:44.120 --> 00:50:46.120
They, especially considering security,

00:50:47.120 --> 00:50:48.120
at least at our institute, they know what they're doing.

00:50:49.120 --> 00:50:51.120
And also ask yourself, do you need all the data?

00:50:52.120 --> 00:50:53.120
If you create an application, do you need to connect

00:50:54.120 --> 00:50:55.120
that application to all the corporate data you have?

00:50:56.120 --> 00:51:02.120
Or can you just extract only the data you need for this application?

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:04.120
It means that in the case of a data breach,

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:07.120
not everything is lost, but just one piece of,

00:51:08.120 --> 00:51:09.120
just a few data points.

00:51:10.120 --> 00:51:12.120
And the second thing is that if you make a selection,

00:51:13.120 --> 00:51:15.120
your application will be quite fast.

00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:18.120
Also, of course, modules make you happy.

00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:21.120
So please do use modules, split your code.

00:51:22.120 --> 00:51:23.120
It's very important to know your user.

00:51:24.120 --> 00:51:25.120
Sjoerd talked quite a lot about this.

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:29.120
And what I really like is that you have to work as a team.

00:51:29.120 --> 00:51:30.120
As you start with such an application,

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:33.120
you put some people together, go sit with each other,

00:51:34.120 --> 00:51:36.120
and just talk, how are we going to do this?

00:51:37.120 --> 00:51:38.120
And how do we like to work together?

00:51:39.120 --> 00:51:42.120
And how do we, well, make this work?

00:51:43.120 --> 00:51:45.120
Just a little reflection on how you interact with each other.

00:51:46.120 --> 00:51:47.120
It can be very important.

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:52.120
And it can be very fruitful to get the energy going in a team.

00:51:53.120 --> 00:51:55.120
And that's all for today.

00:52:00.120 --> 00:52:01.120
Thank you so much, Sjoerd.

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:03.120
That's an amazing presentation.

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:06.120
It's awesome to see both sides of this, too.

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:10.120
And again, we're all clapping, although you can't hear us.

00:52:11.120 --> 00:52:13.120
You can see in the chat.

00:52:14.120 --> 00:52:17.120
There are a lot of great questions over on Slido.

00:52:18.120 --> 00:52:21.120
So I'll start asking a few of them here from Slido,

00:52:22.120 --> 00:52:23.120
especially the anonymous ones.

00:52:24.120 --> 00:52:25.120
But we'd love to have people jumping in

00:52:26.120 --> 00:52:27.120
and asking questions, too.

00:52:27.120 --> 00:52:31.120
So feel free to raise your hand on Zoom, too.

00:52:32.120 --> 00:52:36.120
Well, one of the most upvoted anonymous questions right now is,

00:52:37.120 --> 00:52:39.120
as Cluster Buster began to be used by more people,

00:52:40.120 --> 00:52:42.120
did you face any performance issues?

00:52:43.120 --> 00:52:46.120
And how did you adjust your app to deal with more concurrent users?

00:52:47.120 --> 00:52:48.120
Really good question.

00:52:49.120 --> 00:52:51.120
It's something that we thought about when we first started.

00:52:52.120 --> 00:52:54.120
But the reality is that we create an application for professional use.

00:52:55.120 --> 00:52:58.120
So it's not the case that we have hundreds or thousands of users

00:52:59.120 --> 00:53:00.120
at the same time.

00:53:01.120 --> 00:53:03.120
Sometimes it's 10 users at the same time, for example.

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:05.120
And this is not a problem for us

00:53:06.120 --> 00:53:09.120
because our impact does not fully rely on the amount of users

00:53:10.120 --> 00:53:11.120
that we have.

00:53:12.120 --> 00:53:16.120
Sometimes it's more impactful to have one doctor look at it

00:53:17.120 --> 00:53:19.120
than other doctors look at it.

00:53:20.120 --> 00:53:22.120
So for us, the numbers don't really say that much.

00:53:22.120 --> 00:53:24.120
But because this was a tool made for professional use,

00:53:25.120 --> 00:53:28.120
the number of users was continuously low.

00:53:29.120 --> 00:53:32.120
So we never actually faced any problems in performance.

00:53:33.120 --> 00:53:36.120
And also because we are running this on the OpenShift Kubernetes platform,

00:53:37.120 --> 00:53:40.120
well, it will probably just scale up

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:42.120
if we run into any performance issues.

00:53:43.120 --> 00:53:46.120
This is a more relevant question for following applications

00:53:47.120 --> 00:53:50.120
that we are planning to make public for public use

00:53:50.120 --> 00:53:52.120
instead of for professional use.

00:53:53.120 --> 00:53:55.120
I see another question that says,

00:53:56.120 --> 00:53:57.120
thanks for the great presentation.

00:53:58.120 --> 00:54:00.120
How did you gain the support of the IT team?

00:54:01.120 --> 00:54:03.120
Because for some, there may be a little bit of hesitation

00:54:04.120 --> 00:54:05.120
regarding Shiny.

00:54:06.120 --> 00:54:07.120
Yeah.

00:54:08.120 --> 00:54:09.120
Well, maybe.

00:54:10.120 --> 00:54:11.120
I didn't.

00:54:12.120 --> 00:54:14.120
Well, I did notice some pushback, obviously.

00:54:15.120 --> 00:54:16.120
Someone even literally said to me,

00:54:17.120 --> 00:54:18.120
this is never going to work.

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:20.120
As long as you just stay positive

00:54:21.120 --> 00:54:26.120
and patient at some points,

00:54:27.120 --> 00:54:28.120
I think it will all work out.

00:54:29.120 --> 00:54:35.120
So also what really helped was when we showed the prototype

00:54:36.120 --> 00:54:37.120
or when we showed the application itself,

00:54:38.120 --> 00:54:39.120
this really helped.

00:54:40.120 --> 00:54:42.120
So when we talked to people and I showed the application,

00:54:43.120 --> 00:54:45.120
they all of a sudden understood what we were talking about.

00:54:45.120 --> 00:54:49.120
And this, I believe, was very helpful.

00:54:50.120 --> 00:54:51.120
Yeah.

00:54:52.120 --> 00:54:54.120
That's very important to have a very open-minded talk

00:54:55.120 --> 00:54:56.120
with these IT people.

00:54:57.120 --> 00:54:59.120
Just tell them that you want to put something

00:55:00.120 --> 00:55:01.120
like the cluster bus that you want to put on the internet

00:55:02.120 --> 00:55:04.120
and just try to think and work together

00:55:05.120 --> 00:55:06.120
how we can do this in a secure way.

00:55:07.120 --> 00:55:09.120
And at least our IT departments,

00:55:10.120 --> 00:55:11.120
suddenly what you would say is,

00:55:12.120 --> 00:55:13.120
they understand what you want

00:55:13.120 --> 00:55:15.120
and they are thinking with you.

00:55:16.120 --> 00:55:19.120
Don't try to make them think against you,

00:55:20.120 --> 00:55:21.120
but try to find a common solution

00:55:22.120 --> 00:55:24.120
which actually works and it's possible.

00:55:25.120 --> 00:55:29.120
Also, maybe the crisis helped out a little bit.

00:55:30.120 --> 00:55:31.120
So in this case, it was, let's get it done.

00:55:32.120 --> 00:55:33.120
That was also the mindset.

00:55:34.120 --> 00:55:36.120
So at some points we had to just push through

00:55:37.120 --> 00:55:39.120
and say, well, we need to do this.

00:55:40.120 --> 00:55:42.120
And I guess that's different in normal situations.

00:55:43.120 --> 00:55:45.120
But apart from that, I think a good honest talk,

00:55:46.120 --> 00:55:50.120
as Joep said, and showing what your ideas are really helps.

00:55:52.120 --> 00:55:53.120
Definitely.

00:55:54.120 --> 00:55:55.120
Thank you both.

00:55:56.120 --> 00:55:58.120
Yves, I see you asked a question in Slido

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:00.120
and I'd love to pull in some people

00:56:01.120 --> 00:56:02.120
if you want to ask anything live.

00:56:03.120 --> 00:56:04.120
I fixed the ability to unmute yourself

00:56:05.120 --> 00:56:06.120
if you want to jump in.

00:56:07.120 --> 00:56:08.120
And the question is,

00:56:09.120 --> 00:56:11.120
can you say anything about the updating

00:56:12.120 --> 00:56:14.120
the frequency of the data,

00:56:15.120 --> 00:56:16.120
the update frequency of the data

00:56:17.120 --> 00:56:18.120
in SQLite in production?

00:56:19.120 --> 00:56:20.120
Yeah.

00:56:21.120 --> 00:56:23.120
They send the data to us once a day

00:56:24.120 --> 00:56:28.120
and it's usually in the morning

00:56:29.120 --> 00:56:30.120
and now the data science team starts in the morning

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:32.120
with all the extraction and stuff like that

00:56:33.120 --> 00:56:34.120
and they prepare the data sets that we use

00:56:35.120 --> 00:56:36.120
and usually around noon,

00:56:37.120 --> 00:56:39.120
we run our scripts to create a database.

00:56:40.120 --> 00:56:42.120
So it's created on a daily basis.

00:56:43.120 --> 00:56:45.120
So once a day, we create a new database

00:56:46.120 --> 00:56:50.120
with the latest numbers from yesterday.

00:56:51.120 --> 00:56:52.120
So it's once a day.

00:56:53.120 --> 00:56:56.120
But if you want to do it more often,

00:56:57.120 --> 00:56:58.120
it's quite easy.

00:56:59.120 --> 00:57:00.120
You can run it every hour,

00:57:01.120 --> 00:57:02.120
but the new data is only available once a day.

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:04.120
Great.

00:57:05.120 --> 00:57:06.120
Thank you.

00:57:07.120 --> 00:57:08.120
And I just put in the chat,

00:57:09.120 --> 00:57:10.120
feel free to raise your hand

00:57:11.120 --> 00:57:12.120
if you want to ask your question live

00:57:13.120 --> 00:57:14.120
so you don't have to just keep hearing me repeating them.

00:57:15.120 --> 00:57:16.120
But the next one was,

00:57:17.120 --> 00:57:18.120
which model was used to define the clusters?

00:57:19.120 --> 00:57:20.120
Right.

00:57:21.120 --> 00:57:22.120
So from an epidemiological standpoint,

00:57:23.120 --> 00:57:24.120
I cannot really answer that question,

00:57:25.120 --> 00:57:26.120
but I can answer how the data got constructed.

00:57:27.120 --> 00:57:29.120
So every time someone got a positive test result,

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:32.120
he or she was called by one of the employees at the MHSS

00:57:33.120 --> 00:57:34.120
and was asked,

00:57:35.120 --> 00:57:36.120
with whom have you been in contact?

00:57:37.120 --> 00:57:38.120
Where have you been?

00:57:39.120 --> 00:57:40.120
Where do you think it's most likely

00:57:41.120 --> 00:57:42.120
that you've contracted the virus?

00:57:43.120 --> 00:57:44.120
And once three or more people were saying

00:57:45.120 --> 00:57:46.120
that they most likely contracted the virus

00:57:47.120 --> 00:57:48.120
at a specific place,

00:57:49.120 --> 00:57:50.120
we would call that a cluster.

00:57:51.120 --> 00:57:52.120
Obviously, if you scale up,

00:57:53.120 --> 00:57:54.120
you would call it an outbreak or a super outbreak.

00:57:55.120 --> 00:57:58.120
And the MHSS would write down these clusters,

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:00.120
and they would send that to the RIVM.

00:58:01.120 --> 00:58:02.120
So that's the starting point

00:58:03.120 --> 00:58:04.120
for us to use for our visualizations.

00:58:05.120 --> 00:58:08.120
This was a separate data file that they sent us.

00:58:13.120 --> 00:58:14.120
Thank you.

00:58:15.120 --> 00:58:16.120
Thank you for an awesome presentation.

00:58:17.120 --> 00:58:19.120
Can I ask you if you consider not using a database?

00:58:21.120 --> 00:58:23.120
We have considered this.

00:58:24.120 --> 00:58:25.120
At first,

00:58:26.120 --> 00:58:27.120
different ways to go.

00:58:27.120 --> 00:58:28.120
We were not really sure

00:58:29.120 --> 00:58:30.120
what would be the best way to go.

00:58:31.120 --> 00:58:32.120
So we started out with the database

00:58:33.120 --> 00:58:34.120
and eventually stuck with it.

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:36.120
But this is one of those things

00:58:37.120 --> 00:58:38.120
that from time to time you need to reevaluate.

00:58:39.120 --> 00:58:41.120
Like, is this the right way for Cluster Buster 2.0?

00:58:42.120 --> 00:58:43.120
Is this what you would do?

00:58:44.120 --> 00:58:45.120
I'm not totally convinced that we would.

00:58:46.120 --> 00:58:48.120
But yeah, there is something to say

00:58:49.120 --> 00:58:50.120
for using databases

00:58:51.120 --> 00:58:52.120
and something to say for using pins

00:58:53.120 --> 00:58:55.120
and just our objects.

00:58:56.120 --> 00:58:57.120
You have something to add to that, Job?

00:59:00.120 --> 00:59:02.120
Yeah, well, the great thing is that, of course,

00:59:03.120 --> 00:59:04.120
in the database,

00:59:05.120 --> 00:59:06.120
there are multiple tables you want to use.

00:59:07.120 --> 00:59:08.120
And it's very easy to make relations

00:59:09.120 --> 00:59:10.120
between these tables.

00:59:11.120 --> 00:59:13.120
Therefore, you use a database.

00:59:14.120 --> 00:59:15.120
Also, if you put this information

00:59:16.120 --> 00:59:17.120
in our object or in our environment,

00:59:18.120 --> 00:59:19.120
it's...

00:59:20.120 --> 00:59:22.120
For me, it's more difficult to work with.

00:59:22.120 --> 00:59:24.120
A database is such an easy object.

00:59:25.120 --> 00:59:26.120
And it's a single file.

00:59:27.120 --> 00:59:28.120
And you can work with it in IR.

00:59:29.120 --> 00:59:30.120
But you can also open it

00:59:31.120 --> 00:59:32.120
in an SQLite browser

00:59:33.120 --> 00:59:34.120
just to inspect your data.

00:59:35.120 --> 00:59:36.120
Or you can use it in...

00:59:37.120 --> 00:59:38.120
Also, you can use it

00:59:39.120 --> 00:59:40.120
in multiple applications.

00:59:41.120 --> 00:59:42.120
It's much easier to have

00:59:43.120 --> 00:59:44.120
multiple file connectors

00:59:45.120 --> 00:59:46.120
to the database.

00:59:47.120 --> 00:59:48.120
So for me,

00:59:49.120 --> 00:59:50.120
I think I prefer a database

00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:53.120
over some file-based object.

00:59:56.120 --> 00:59:58.120
So maybe it's a matter of taste.

01:00:00.120 --> 01:00:01.120
Yeah.

01:00:02.120 --> 01:00:03.120
One of the ways you could look at this

01:00:04.120 --> 01:00:05.120
is also from the performance perspective.

01:00:06.120 --> 01:00:07.120
So right now, we are iterating over our database

01:00:08.120 --> 01:00:09.120
to give back the data

01:00:10.120 --> 01:00:11.120
from a specific region.

01:00:12.120 --> 01:00:13.120
This is not a very fast operation.

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:15.120
So if you use...

01:00:16.120 --> 01:00:17.120
I forgot the name of the package.

01:00:18.120 --> 01:00:19.120
But we do monitor

01:00:20.120 --> 01:00:21.120
the performance of the application.

01:00:22.120 --> 01:00:23.120
And if we would notice

01:00:24.120 --> 01:00:25.120
that it would take a lot of time

01:00:26.120 --> 01:00:27.120
to produce the visualizations,

01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:29.120
then I would definitely consider

01:00:30.120 --> 01:00:31.120
backing off of a database.

01:00:32.120 --> 01:00:33.120
So there are a multitude

01:00:34.120 --> 01:00:35.120
of considerations you need to make.

01:00:36.120 --> 01:00:37.120
So for now, it's fine.

01:00:38.120 --> 01:00:39.120
Maybe because of our small user group

01:00:40.120 --> 01:00:41.120
or the amount of data that we have.

01:00:42.120 --> 01:00:43.120
But this is certainly a question

01:00:44.120 --> 01:00:45.120
that's on our mind.

01:00:48.120 --> 01:00:49.120
Thank you.

01:00:50.120 --> 01:00:51.120
You have your hand raised, too.

01:00:54.120 --> 01:00:55.120
Yeah. Hi.

01:00:56.120 --> 01:00:57.120
I'm Nimish Sheth.

01:00:58.120 --> 01:00:59.120
First of all, thank you

