But it is, did you have any functionality

01:17:33.120 --> 01:17:35.120
within your apps to send individual

01:17:35.120 --> 01:17:38.120
level data to municipalities?

01:17:41.120 --> 01:17:42.120
No.

01:17:44.120 --> 01:17:45.120
No, we didn't.

01:17:45.120 --> 01:17:47.120
So we

01:17:47.120 --> 01:17:49.120
added a download button at

01:17:49.120 --> 01:17:51.120
a specific point

01:17:51.120 --> 01:17:52.120
in our dashboard.

01:17:52.120 --> 01:17:54.120
But we were

01:17:54.120 --> 01:17:55.120
very wary of

01:17:55.120 --> 01:17:57.120
providing options to download

01:17:57.120 --> 01:17:59.120
the data for obvious

01:17:59.120 --> 01:18:01.120
reasons. You don't want this data

01:18:01.120 --> 01:18:03.120
to just float around.

01:18:03.120 --> 01:18:05.120
So we limited the

01:18:05.120 --> 01:18:07.120
sharing of personal data. There are

01:18:07.120 --> 01:18:09.120
other options in which the MHSs can

01:18:09.120 --> 01:18:11.120
get personal,

01:18:11.120 --> 01:18:13.120
get more detailed information from

01:18:13.120 --> 01:18:15.120
the RFEM, but most of them already have

01:18:15.120 --> 01:18:17.120
it. So no, through

01:18:17.120 --> 01:18:19.120
the Cluster Buster, we were not really

01:18:19.120 --> 01:18:21.120
providing any personal details.

01:18:22.120 --> 01:18:24.120
This was also not the point of the Cluster Buster.

01:18:25.120 --> 01:18:27.120
So the point of the Cluster Buster

01:18:27.120 --> 01:18:29.120
was to

01:18:29.120 --> 01:18:31.120
help doctors and epidemiologists

01:18:31.120 --> 01:18:33.120
gain an understanding of the COVID-19 situation.

01:18:33.120 --> 01:18:35.120
And this is,

01:18:35.120 --> 01:18:37.120
the numbers were so great, the individual

01:18:37.120 --> 01:18:39.120
level was not important.

