just try.

01:19:22.120 --> 01:19:24.120
SHINee modules,

01:19:24.120 --> 01:19:26.120
when you start, it's a bit difficult

01:19:26.120 --> 01:19:28.120
to wrap your head around, but as soon

01:19:28.120 --> 01:19:30.120
as you get it done, it's getting easier

01:19:30.120 --> 01:19:32.120
and easier.

01:19:32.120 --> 01:19:34.120
Just try.

01:19:34.120 --> 01:19:36.120
And ask around, of course, if you don't

01:19:36.120 --> 01:19:38.120
know what to do.

01:19:39.120 --> 01:19:41.120
One of the

01:19:41.120 --> 01:19:43.120
last questions I saw on Slido was

01:19:43.120 --> 01:19:45.120
for huge amounts of data,

01:19:45.120 --> 01:19:47.120
have you tested out file types like

01:19:47.120 --> 01:19:49.120
RDA or PDF?

01:19:49.120 --> 01:19:51.120
Like RDA or Parquet

01:19:51.120 --> 01:19:53.120
to store your data set within your containers?

01:19:53.120 --> 01:19:55.120
It's

01:19:55.120 --> 01:19:57.120
not for Cluster Buster. We have other

01:19:57.120 --> 01:19:59.120
applications with huge files

01:19:59.120 --> 01:20:01.120
with many data where

01:20:01.120 --> 01:20:03.120
it's a concern, but we started with Cluster Buster.

01:20:03.120 --> 01:20:05.120
The current way of

01:20:05.120 --> 01:20:07.120
using SQLite was fast enough.

01:20:07.120 --> 01:20:09.120
Now we're running

01:20:09.120 --> 01:20:11.120
into situations where we think

01:20:11.120 --> 01:20:13.120
it might be faster.

01:20:13.120 --> 01:20:15.120
Getting it faster would be nice.

01:20:15.120 --> 01:20:17.120
But for other applications,

01:20:17.120 --> 01:20:19.120
we want to look into it.

01:20:19.120 --> 01:20:21.120
But it's very

01:20:21.120 --> 01:20:23.120
depending on the type of data

01:20:23.120 --> 01:20:25.120
and how you use it in your application.

01:20:25.120 --> 01:20:27.120
So actually, when you're

01:20:27.120 --> 01:20:29.120
starting off,

01:20:29.120 --> 01:20:31.120
it's always good to think about it and do

01:20:31.120 --> 01:20:33.120
some tests.

01:20:33.120 --> 01:20:35.120
It really depends

01:20:35.120 --> 01:20:37.120
on what you want to do with your data.

